The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Dilip Banerjee, or Hatkata Dilip, and three of his accomplices have been found guilty of murdering two persons in Nayapatti, Salt Lake, in 2005. The Barrackpore sub-divisional judicial magistrates court, while delivering the verdict on Monday, said the sentence would be announced on November 1. Footballers Sasthi Duley and Dipankar Roy have been cleared of charges of involvement in the case.

 Manoj Shaw, a Bihar MLA and vice-president of the RJD, moved Calcutta High Court on Monday for anticipatory bail. He has been accused in an FIR, lodged with Howrah GRP, of snatching the belongings of his co-passengers during a train journey a month ago. Shaw claimed the charges were false. The plea will come up for hearing in a couple of days.

 The bail plea of Govind Sarda, the principal accused in the blood kit scam, came up for hearing before the Calcutta High Court division bench of Justice D.P. Sengupta and Justice B. Somadder on Monday. Appearing for the state, a panel lawyer submitted that advocate-general Balai Ray could not turn up because of illness. The bench deferred the hearing to Wednesday.

 Justice Kalyan Jyoti Sengupta of Calcutta High Court issued a showcause notice to the commissioner of Howrah Municipal Corporation on Monday for his failure to provide covered vats on GT Road. The court had earlier asked the commissioner to place a few covered vats beside the highway. The judge had also showcaused Bally Municipality for its failure to maintain GT Road.

 Two persons died in separate railway accidents in Calcutta and Howrah on Monday morning. Gopeswar Malik, 65, a resident of Jagannath Ghosh Road in south Calcutta, was run over by a train near Ballygunge station. Bhadreswar Ghorui, 48, a resident of North Joypur in Howrah, was hit by a speeding train near Bally station. Ghorui was taken to the district hospital, where he was pronounced dead.

 Kamala Ghorui, 70, died after being run over by an unidentified vehicle in Jagachha, Howrah, on Monday morning. Police are looking for the vehicle. 

 An unidentified man, believed to be a porter, died after a motorcycle knocked him down at the crossing of Brabourne Road and Armenian Street, under Burrabazar police station, on Monday morning. The man died while being taken to Medical College and Hospital. The motorcycle driver has been arrested. 

 Relatives of Taseer Ali, 20, admitted to RG Kar Medical College and Hospital, accused the authorities of negligence after he died on Monday afternoon. Ali was admitted to the hospital around 9 am with high fever. 

 Ved Jaiswal, 39, an advocate of Howrah court, was found hanging at his residence under Golabari police station on Monday. A probe suggested that he had been suffering from depression.

 The Indian Institute of Social Welfare and Business Management on Monday launched a three-month certificate-training course on disaster management.

 TO Rotary Club of Calcutta city 

 of joy for organising a free eye-screening camp




